'''Take Minato Jinja''' (たけみなとみじんじゃ) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Ishii, Tokushima|Ishii, Tokushima]], Tokushima Prefecture, Japan. It is a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}} and regarded as an ancestral shrine of [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa-taisha]].

== History ==
The year of the shrine's founding is unknown. The current shrine building was constructed in [[:en:Kyōhō|1720]] 5.

The shrine was highly revered by the [[:en:Hachisuka clan|Hachisuka clan]], feudal lords of the Tokushima Domain. During its festival, members of the clan would often personally visit or send representatives. In [[:en:Kan'ei|1627]] 4, [[:en:Hachisuka Mitsutaka|Hachisuka Mitsutaka]] prayed at the shrine and reported miraculous occurrences. Additionally, a division of the shrine's spirit was transferred to {{ill|Suwa Shrine (Tokushima City)|ja|諏訪神社 (徳島市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Shrine (Tokushima City)|qq=}} near [[:en:Tokushima Castle|Tokushima Castle]] for easier access during times when the flooding of the Ayukui River prevented direct visits to Take Minato Jinja.

According to the shrine's historical records, "In the tenth year of [[:en:Hōki|Hōki]] during the reign of Emperor [[:en:Emperor Kōnin|Kōnin]] (779 CE), the Suwa Daimyōjin of Nakata District, Awa Province, was transferred and enshrined at the Minato Shrine in Suwa, Shinano Province (modern-day [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa-taisha]], Nagano Prefecture)." This implies that {{ill|Takeminakata no Mikoto|ja|建御名方命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata no Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タケミナカタ}}, known for his mythological dispute with {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武御雷神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, originally hailed from Awa Province and that Suwa Taisha's origins trace back to Awa, as recorded in the shrine's documents.<ref>Sasada Takashi, *The Imperial Capital Yamato was Awa*, Sun Lotus Research Institute, 2024, pp. 173-185.</ref>

== Deities ==
* {{ill|Takeminakata no Mikoto|ja|建御名方命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata no Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タケミナカタ}}
* {{ill|Yasakatome no Mikoto|ja|八坂刀売命|1=Yasakatome|2=ja|3=八坂刀売命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasakatome no Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 八坂刀売神}}

== Auxiliary Shrines ==
* {{ill|Earth God Shrine|ja|地神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Earth God Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}

== Access ==
* Approximately a 25-minute walk from [[:en:Shimoura Station|Shimoura Station]] on the [[:en:Tokushima Line|Tokushima Line]] (JR Shikoku).
* Approximately a 20-minute walk from [[:en:Ushinoshima Station|Ushijima Station]] on the same line.

