== History ==
The year of the shrine's founding is unknown. The current shrine building was constructed in [[:en:Kyōhō|1720]] 5.

The shrine was highly revered by the [[:en:Hachisuka clan|Hachisuka clan]], feudal lords of the Tokushima Domain. During its festival, members of the clan would often personally visit or send representatives. In [[:en:Kan'ei|1627]] 4, [[:en:Hachisuka Mitsutaka|Hachisuka Mitsutaka]] prayed at the shrine and reported miraculous occurrences. Additionally, a division of the shrine's spirit was transferred to {{ill|Suwa Shrine (Tokushima City)|ja|諏訪神社 (徳島市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Shrine (Tokushima City)|qq=}} near [[:en:Tokushima Castle|Tokushima Castle]] for easier access during times when the flooding of the Ayukui River prevented direct visits to Take Minato Jinja.

According to the shrine's historical records, "In the tenth year of [[:en:Hōki|Hōki]] during the reign of Emperor [[:en:Emperor Kōnin|Kōnin]] (779 CE), the Suwa Daimyōjin of Nakata District, Awa Province, was transferred and enshrined at the Minato Shrine in Suwa, Shinano Province (modern-day [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa-taisha]], Nagano Prefecture)." This implies that {{ill|Takeminakata no Mikoto|ja|建御名方命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeminakata no Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to タケミナカタ|1=Takeminakata|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q9150391}}, known for his mythological dispute with {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武御雷神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, originally hailed from Awa Province and that Suwa Taisha's origins trace back to Awa, as recorded in the shrine's documents.<ref>Sasada Takashi, *The Imperial Capital Yamato was Awa*, Sun Lotus Research Institute, 2024, pp. 173-185.</ref>

